PROMPT inner_join_explanation
WITH BUDGET 6000 tokens
USING MODEL "claude-sonnet-4-5"

SELECT
    system_role("You are a SQL database expert specializing in JOIN operations, relational algebra, and query optimization with deep knowledge of how different JOIN types work and their practical applications.")

GENERATE
    explain_inner_join("Explain INNER JOIN in SQL, covering: the definition of INNER JOIN as a type of join that returns only rows where there is a matching value in both tables being joined, the syntax using either explicit INNER JOIN ... ON or implicit comma-separated tables with WHERE conditions, how INNER JOIN works by creating a Cartesian product of the two tables and then filtering to keep only rows where the join condition is true, the difference between INNER JOIN and other join types including LEFT JOIN which returns all rows from the left table plus matches from right, RIGHT JOIN which returns all rows from the right table plus matches from left, and FULL OUTER JOIN which returns all rows from both tables, concrete examples showing two sample tables like Customers (id, name, city) and Orders (id, customer_id, product, amount) and demonstrating how SELECT c.name, o.product FROM Customers c INNER JOIN Orders o ON c.id = o.customer_id returns only customers who have placed orders along with their order details, while customers without orders and orders without valid customer references are excluded, the result set characteristics where INNER JOIN never produces NULL values from the join operation itself since it only includes rows with matches in both tables, performance considerations including how database engines optimize INNER JOINs using indexes on join columns and how the order of tables can affect query execution plans, common use cases such as retrieving related data from normalized database tables, filtering data based on existence in another table, and combining information from multiple tables where relationships must exist, best practices including using table aliases for readability, ensuring proper indexing on join columns for performance, and choosing appropriate join types based on whether you need all rows from one or both tables versus only matching rows.")
WITH OUTPUT BUDGET 2500 tokens, TEMPERATURE 0.2, FORMAT markdown;